  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "The likelihood of a hypothesis given observed data is the probability of having observed that data if the hypothesis were true. It asks: how well does this hypothesis explain what we actually saw? If a coin is fair (hypothesis: p=0.5p = 0.5), the probability of observing 8 heads in 10 flips is about 0.044. If the coin is biased (p=0.8p = 0.8), the probability of that same outcome is about 0.302. The biased-coin hypothesis has higher likelihood — it makes the observed data more probable.\n",
